# Operational Safety

## File Operations
- Do not directly edit binary files, archives, media, model weights, lock databases, or large generated artifacts. Regenerate them with the project toolchain when needed.
- Do not delete, overwrite, or mass-move files unless the user requested it or the plan explicitly requires it.
- Preserve unrelated user changes in a dirty working tree; work around them instead of reverting them.

## Secrets And Environment
- Never write secrets, tokens, passwords, private keys, or real credentials into tracked files.
- Do not modify global machine/user configuration (`git config`, shell profiles, global package managers, system env) unless explicitly requested.
- Treat `.env*`, credentials files, and deployment config as sensitive; edit templates/docs instead when possible.

## Database And Data
- Never run destructive DB operations (`DROP`, `TRUNCATE`, bulk `DELETE`/`UPDATE`) without a backup/rollback plan and explicit user confirmation.
- Prefer migrations over ad hoc schema changes; include rollback or recovery notes for risky migrations.
- Use parameterized queries and transaction boundaries for data changes.

## External Effects
- Ask before actions with external side effects: production deploys, billing changes, sending emails/messages, publishing packages, or mutating remote services.
- Prefer dry runs and scoped test environments before touching production.
